      <h1 id="assignment-1">Assignment 1</h1>

<h2 id="linux-questions">Linux Questions</h2>

<ol class="question">
    <li>
    <p>This question has several parts.
    Here is the background:
    <strong>alice</strong>, <strong>bob</strong> and <strong>chloe</strong> are users on a system.
    <strong>bob</strong> is a member of a group named <strong>secret</strong>, but
    <strong>alice</strong> and <strong>chloe</strong> are not members of that group.</p>

    <p>The directories <code>/home/alice/share</code> and <code>home/alice/share/x</code>
    are owned by <strong>alice</strong> with group owner <strong>secret</strong>. 
    Further, the directory <code>/home/alice/share/x</code> has permissions 751
    and
    the directory <code>home/alice/share/y</code> has permissions 710.</p>

    <p>The directory <code>/home/alice/share</code> contains two files:
    <code>ghi</code>, with permissions 644 and <code>jkl</code>, with permissions 400.
    The directory  <code>/home/alice/share/x</code> contains two files:
    <code>abc</code> and <code>def</code>, both with permissions 644.
    All four files are owned by <strong>alice</strong>.
    <code>jkl</code> and <code>def</code>  have group owner <strong>alice</strong>.
    <code>ghi</code> and <code>abc</code> have group owner <strong>secret</strong>.</p>

    <ol>
      <li>If a user is logged in as <strong>alice</strong>, which of the following
  operations is allowed?
  Which operations are not allowed?
        <ol>
          <li><code>ls /home/alice/share</code></li>
          <li><code>ls /home/alice/share/x</code></li>
          <li><code>cat /home/alice/share/ghi</code></li>
          <li><code>cat /home/alice/share/jkl</code></li>
          <li><code>cat /home/alice/share/x/abc</code></li>
          <li><code>cat /home/alice/share/x/def</code></li>
        </ol>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>Repeat the first part fo a user logged in as <strong>bob</strong></p>
      </li>
      <li>Repeat the first part fo a user logged in as <strong>chloe</strong></li>
    </ol>

    <p>Use the following grid to report your answers to this question.
    Use ‘+’ for allowed and ‘0’ for not allowed.</p>

    <table class="grid">
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td> </td>
          <td><strong>alice</strong></td>
          <td><strong>bob</strong></td>
          <td><strong>chloe</strong></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>ls /home/alice/share</code></td>
          <td> </td>
          <td> </td>
          <td> </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>ls /home/alice/share/x</code></td>
          <td> </td>
          <td> </td>
          <td> </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>cat /home/alice/share/ghi</code></td>
          <td> </td>
          <td> </td>
          <td> </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>cat /home/alice/share/jkl</code></td>
          <td> </td>
          <td> </td>
          <td> </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>cat /home/alice/share/x/abc</code></td>
          <td> </td>
          <td> </td>
          <td> </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>cat /home/alice/share/x/def</code></td>
          <td> </td>
          <td> </td>
          <td> </td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

  </li>
    
<li>
    <p>We wish to set the permissions on the directory <code>/home/alice/public</code> so that
        everyone can copy files into the directory but not list the directory.
        The group owner of the directory should have no access at all.
        The owner of the directory, <strong>alice</strong>, should have all possible access
        to the directory.
        Give the <code>chmod</code> command that will set the permissions properly. </p>
  </li>



<li>
   Consider the directory `/home/alice/share/x`.
   <ol>
        <li>
            Give the relative path to that directory if the current
            directory is `/home/alice/share`
        </li>
        <li>
            Give the relative path to that directory if the current
            directory is `/home/alice/share/y`
        </li>
        <li>
            Give the relative path to that directory if the current
            directory is `/home/alice`
        </li>
      </ol>  
</li>

<li>
    Give a command that pipes a long listing of the directory <code>/etc</code>
    to the <code>sort</code> command so that the listing is in order by file size.
</li>

<li>
    Give the recommended command (for Ubuntu/Mint) for getting the
    apache web server to reread the configuration file without restarting
    the server.
</li>
</ol>

